response_text:
Below are (A) concise legal guidance on how strongly you can word the finding about the nine‑dash line without overstating the legal position, and (B) three draft resolution texts you can use or adapt (Strong, Moderate, and Technical versions). At the end I note why certain word choices were selected and recommend a final pick.

A. Legal guidance — how forceful you can be, without overstating
- The safest, accurate statements:
  - “The nine‑dash line has no legal basis under the 1982 United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea (UNCLOS).”
  - “The nine‑dash line is inconsistent with UNCLOS and with the arbitral tribunal’s Award in The Republic of the Philippines v. The People’s Republic of China (PCA Case No. 2013–19, Award, 12 July 2016).”
  These formulations are factually supportable. The 2016 PCA award explicitly concluded that any historic rights in areas within the nine‑dash line that exceed entitlements under UNCLOS have no legal basis.

- What to avoid if you want to minimize legal overstatement:
  - Avoid absolute, universal formulations such as “China’s nine‑dash line is illegal under international law” without reference to the arbitral award or UNCLOS. That can be framed as a legal conclusion which some states (and China) dispute politically.
  - Avoid stating the arbitral award is “binding on all states.” It is binding on the parties to the arbitration (primarily the Philippines and, procedurally, the tribunal), and its findings are an authoritative interpretation of UNCLOS, but China refused to participate and does not accept the award.

- Middle ground that is still strong and defensible:
  - “The nine‑dash line is incompatible with the rights and obligations set out in UNCLOS and, as affirmed by the 2016 arbitral tribunal, lacks a valid legal basis to claim maritime entitlements beyond those provided for in UNCLOS.” This ties the conclusion to the treaty and the award and avoids asserting universal bindingness beyond those bases.

- Practical/political note:
  - Political organs (e.g., a legislature or intergovernmental body) can legitimately “condemn” or “declare” a state’s conduct unlawful as a matter of policy. That is different from a judicial ruling; but if accuracy matters, anchor statements to UNCLOS and the PCA award.

B. Draft resolution language
Below are three alternative versions you can use depending on how forceful you want the resolution to be. Each contains sample preambular and operative paragraphs. You can mix and match clauses.

1) Strong version (politically robust; cites PCA award; calls out non‑compliance)
Preamble
- Recalling the 1982 United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea (UNCLOS) and the obligation of all States to respect its provisions concerning maritime entitlements, boundary delimitation, and the rights of coastal States;
- Noting the Award of the Arbitral Tribunal in The Republic of the Philippines v. The People’s Republic of China (PCA Case No. 2013–19, Award, 12 July 2016), which concluded that claims to historic rights within the so‑called “nine‑dash line” that exceed maritime entitlements under UNCLOS have no legal basis;
- Expressing concern about actions that assert or enforce maritime claims inconsistent with UNCLOS, including land reclamation, construction, militarization, and interference with navigation and resource activities;

Operative
1. Condemns the assertion and enforcement of maritime claims based on the nine‑dash line as having no legal basis under UNCLOS and as contrary to the PCA Award of 12 July 2016;
2. Calls upon the People’s Republic of China to comply with international law, to respect the rights and entitlements of other States under UNCLOS, and to cease activities that further assert or enforce the nine‑dash line;
3. Urges all parties to the dispute to resolve their differences peacefully, to refrain from the use or threat of force, to stop activities that exacerbate tensions, and to pursue diplomatic or legal means consistent with UNCLOS;
4. Affirms the importance of freedom of navigation and overflight in the South China Sea and calls on all States to refrain from actions that impede these freedoms;
5. Requests relevant international and regional bodies, and all States, to support efforts to ensure compliance with UNCLOS and to assist in confidence‑building measures.

2) Moderate version (firm but cautious; emphasizes inconsistency rather than absolute illegality)
Preamble
- Recalling UNCLOS and the centrality of its rules in determining maritime entitlements;
- Noting the conclusion in the 12 July 2016 Arbitral Award (PCA Case No. 2013–19) that maritime claims based on historic rights within the “nine‑dash line” are inconsistent with UNCLOS;
- Concerned by unilateral actions that increase the risk of confrontation and undermine maritime stability;

Operative
1. Declares that claims to maritime entitlements premised on the “nine‑dash line” are inconsistent with the rights and obligations established by UNCLOS and are not supported by the 2016 Arbitral Award;
2. Calls on the People’s Republic of China and other claimants to respect UNCLOS, to halt activities that assert or expand such claims, and to engage in peaceful dispute settlement consistent with international law;
3. Affirms the importance of maintaining free and lawful navigation and overflight, and of protecting marine resources and the marine environment;
4. Encourages confidence‑building measures, multilateral dialogue, and negotiation toward a legally grounded, peaceful settlement of overlapping maritime claims.

3) Technical/legalist version (measured, precise legal language; for use where legal accuracy is paramount)
Preamble
- Recalling UNCLOS, including provisions governing baselines, territorial seas, exclusive economic zones (EEZs), and continental shelf entitlements;
- Recalling the Award of the Arbitral Tribunal in The Republic of the Philippines v. The People’s Republic of China (PCA Case No. 2013–19, Award, 12 July 2016), which determined, inter alia, that features in the Spratly Islands do not generate EEZs/continental shelf beyond applicable limits and that any historic rights asserted by reference to the “nine‑dash line” were incompatible with UNCLOS;
- Noting that the Tribunal’s conclusions constitute an authoritative interpretation of UNCLOS in the circumstances of that dispute;

Operative
1. Finds that, insofar as they purport to establish maritime entitlements beyond those provided under UNCLOS, claims founded on the “nine‑dash line” lack a basis in UNCLOS and are therefore inconsistent with the Convention as interpreted by the Arbitral Tribunal in its 12 July 2016 Award;
2. Calls upon the Parties to respect the legal framework of UNCLOS and to refrain from actions that assert or attempt to enforce maritime entitlements inconsistent with that framework;
3. Urges use of peaceful dispute settlement procedures provided for in UNCLOS, and encourages parties to submit to or accept processes that will clarify maritime rights and obligations under international law;
4. Requests that coastal States and maritime users continue to observe the rights of navigation and other lawful uses of the sea pending resolution of competing claims.

C. Why these formulations were chosen (brief)
- “Has no legal basis under UNCLOS” and “is inconsistent with UNCLOS” are supportable because the 2016 PCA Award reached precisely that conclusion regarding historic rights to maritime entitlements claimed by reference to the nine‑dash line.
- Avoiding the single word “illegal” (or using it carefully) reduces risk of legal overreach because (a) the PCA award is not universally accepted by all States, and (b) the politicized nature of the dispute means some audiences will contest any categorical statement that a State has violated international law unless it is tied to a judicial/tribunal finding.
- Citing the PCA Award and UNCLOS anchors the political statement in a widely recognized legal instrument and an authoritative arbitral decision.

D. Practical recommendation
- If the resolution is intended for a national legislature or an international body that wants a strong stance: use the Strong or Moderate version, but keep the key factual anchor to UNCLOS and the 2016 Award.
- If the resolution is intended for a forum emphasizing legal precision (e.g., for circulation to legal advisers or an international legal committee), use the Technical version.
- Have your legal counsel review final text to ensure alignment with institutional positions and diplomatic strategy.

If you tell me which forum (national parliament, UN body, regional organization, NGO) and how aggressive you want to be, I can tailor the language further (e.g., add specific references to incidents, dates, or additional operative measures).
